headline: Waymo unveils plan to bring its robotaxi service to Miami
summary: Waymo is gearing up to bring its robotaxi service to Miami which will accelerate an expansion that's been happening while its hobbled rivals remain in its rearview mirror.  As part of the road map unfurled Thursday, Waymo plans to begin testing its driverless Jaguars in Miami next year, giving the robotaxis time to learn their way around Florida's biggest city before they start charging for rides in 2026.  The move comes less than a month after Waymo opened up its robotaxi service to anyone looking for a ride in an 80-square-mile (129-square-kilometer) expanse in Los Angeles, extending its reach beyond its two major markets in Phoenix and San Francisco.

headline: Alphabet's Waymo to expand ride-hailing services to Miami
summary: The company plans to introduce its vehicles to Miami's streets early next year and aims to launch services to riders in 2026, offering ride-hailing through the Waymo One app.  Waymo's expansion comes at a crucial time as the firm is under intense scrutiny from safety regulators following multiple incidents involving autonomous driving technology.  Intense competition in the autonomous vehicle market, particularly from General Motors' Cruise, Amazon's Zoox and newcomer Tesla presents a significant challenge to Waymo's efforts to establish and maintain market dominance in the rapidly evolving self-driving technology sector.

headline: Spotify Wrapped gets the AI treatment through Google partnership
summary: It's that time of year again, and no, I'm not talking about the holiday season or the post-Thanksgiving gym session. Spotify Wrapped is back (SPOT) to remind music lovers of their most listened-to songs and favorite artists from this past year, and it wouldn't be 2024 without a smidge of AI thrown in there. Steven Johnson, the Head of Editorial at Google Labs (GOOG, GOOGL), joins Josh Lipton and Akiko Fujita to talk about the AI partnership with Spotify to build out an AI-generated podcast to accompany users' Wrapped experience, built with Google NotebookLM. "The software effectively looks at your listening history, it knows a little bit about the kind of the artists in question and their... records and their sensibility... and it turns that into this kind of playful banter, discussing what was interesting about your year in music," Johnson tells Yahoo Finance. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Asking for a Trend here. This post was written by Luke Carberry Mogan.
